f   ‘sharp-cutting’ or of any of several other European names with similar meaning."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":8,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705193,"age":17,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":62,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"James Sharpe was born in 1320, in England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs James Sharpe. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1320–":"1320–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Coggeshall, Essex, England":"Coggeshall, Essex, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1320–":"1320–Kuollut","1325–Female":"1325–Kuollut","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1320–Male":"1320–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Coggeshall, Essex, England":"Coggeshall, Essex, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"1320–":"1320–Décédé","1325–Female":"1325–Décédée","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1320–Male":"1320–Décédé","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1328":"1328","Coggeshall, Essex, England":"Coggeshall, Essex, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"James Sharpe est né en 1320, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Mrs James Sharpe. Il est décédé dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1320–":"1320–Verstorben","1325–Female":